Two options for LLVM from Rust:

1. **Inkwell** — Safe Rust wrapper around LLVM C API:
```rust
use inkwell::context::Context;
let context = Context::create();
let module = context.create_module("my_lang");
let builder = context.create_builder();

let i64_type = context.i64_type();
let fn_type = i64_type.fn_type(&[i64_type.into(), i64_type.into()], false);
let function = module.add_function("add", fn_type, None);
```

2. **llvm-sys** — Raw FFI bindings (more control, less safe)

For Cranelift (simpler):
```rust
use cranelift::prelude::*;
let mut builder = FunctionBuilder::new(&mut func, &mut builder_ctx);
let a = builder.append_block_param(block, types::I64);
let b = builder.append_block_param(block, types::I64);
let sum = builder.ins().iadd(a, b);
```

My suggestion: Start with Cranelift to get your language working end-to-end fast. Switch to LLVM (via Inkwell) later if you need better optimization. The frontend (parser, type checker) is the same regardless of backend.
